huntBios.GENERAL_INFORMATION: This unit encompasses low desert to high mountain terrain.  Moose are found on both sides of Flaming Gorge Reservoir, with the majority found in the higher elevations west of Flaming Gorge Reservoir.  This unit is a general season deer unit and the West Daggett subunit is a general season elk unit; this area is heavily utilized during these other hunts with many people camping out during the seasons.
huntBios.SAFETY_CONS:
Due to recent storms, several roads in the 3 Corners vicinity have washed out and are impassable to any vehicle, including side by sides and ATVs. Please do not harm the habitat by trying to drive off road around wash outs. Driving off road is illegal.

Cellular phone coverage is spotty on this hunt unit. Satellite phones do work in the area. A "Spot Tracker" type of satellite messaging device for safety can be used if you decide to camp in an area without cell phone service and do not wish to travel to reach service. Make sure someone knows where you plan to camp and when you will return.

Camps should be kept clean to prevent bear incidents. Food should be kept inside vehicles or bear-proof containers. Coolers are not bear-proof. Bears have gotten into camps in the past in this unit. Number and severity of bear incidents differ by year depending on weather and other food availability. Meat and garbage should be put away inside a vehicle or hung in a tree above 8 feet off the ground and 3 feet away from the trunk or any branches of the tree.

Moose can be unpredictable and dangerous if you encroach into their space. Females can be protective of young and may charge if they perceive you as a threat. Males can be defensive, especially during the rut.
huntBios.WEATHER_CONS: The weather on this hunt unit can vary dramatically during the hunting season.  Be prepared for rain, lightning, snow, wind and heat.  It is quite common on clear mornings for clouds to build through the morning and have thunderstorms in the afternoon.  Be very cautious of lightning if you’re crossing high ridges or exposed slopes.  Early fall snow storms occur occasionally in this area.  Most years the snow will melt off within a day or two until through the first week of October.  Some years a big snowstorm will hit the beginning of October and make some roads impassable.

huntBios.BIOLOGIST_NOTES:
Location of harvest:
Moose are very large animals and difficult to haul long distances. They are often found near or in water. Do not shoot if you cannot retrieve the animal where it may go down, such as in a lake or stream. Choose your shot wisely; you may have to wait for it to move to a better location. If you cannot retrieve the moose, do not shoot; this is not an excuse for wasting game.

Migration Patterns:
Moose do not show a definite migration pattern on the North Slope. They are not as dependent on water sources during the winter months. Snow depth also does not seem to affect where they are located.

Scouting Tips:
In the Uintas, locating a bull moose is the hardest part of the hunt. Scouting trips are highly recommended so you become familiar with the unit and know the size of bull you will most likely harvest. Take your fishing pole along and enjoy the mountain lakes and streams. A good spotting scope and binoculars are essential. Bull moose can move long distances, especially during the rut when they are in search of cows so you may not see the same moose on different scouting trips. Moose do move during the year, so where you find them in the winter and summer may not be where they are in the fall. When the rut starts, a bull moose may move many miles in one day so don’t count on finding the same bull in an area on consecutive days.

Behavior:
Like other wildlife, moose are most active in the early mornings and evenings, but they can be up and moving any time of the day. Most of the time, they are found in mountain riparian areas near lakes and streams, most often where there are willows or aspen. During the rut, bulls and cows will call to attract mates. This can be useful in finding bulls in the thick vegetation they are often in. Bulls are sometimes attracted to thrashing willows if they think it’s another bull. You may be able to use this trick to lure them into a different area for a better shot.

Moose rut:
The moose rut usually runs during September and October.

Where to find moose:
The majority of the moose are found on the West Daggett portion of the unit. It is generally higher in elevation and has more water than the 3 Corners side. During the hunt, moose will generally be found along streams and in aspen stands, but they may also be found in conifer stands moving between areas.

Recommended areas in the West Daggett/3 Corners:
Good areas to hunt include Carter Creek, Spirit Lake, Sheep Lake, Sheep Creek, and Moose Ponds area. These areas are all on USFS lands. Occasionally a bull can be found in the 3 Corners area and Willow Creek drainage. There is private property in this area so you should receive written permission from landowners if you wish to hunt their property.

huntMaster.HARVEST_REPORTING: REQUIRED: click here or call 1-800-221-0659 to report your harvest. You must report your harvest, even if you did not take an animal, within 30 days of the season end date that is printed on your permit; failure to do so may result in you not being able to apply for big game species in subsequent years. Submitting teeth or other biological samples from your animal, or having your animal checked by a DWR representative or CWMU operator does NOT fulfill your mandatory harvest reporting requirement.

huntBoundaryInfos.LAND_OWNERSHIP: 90% Public Land - US Forest Service and BLM lands.
huntBoundaryInfos.CAMPGRND_INFO:
All Campgrounds on this unit are managed by the US Forest Service and BLM. Camping outside of official campgrounds is also permitted on most of the public lands. Please direct all questions regarding campground availability and other camping questions to the US Forest Service. Maps and camping regulations are available on their websites.
Ashley National Forest: http://www.fs.usda.gov/main/ashley/home
Uinta-Wasatch-Cache National Forest: http://www.fs.usda.gov/main/uwcnf/
huntBoundaryInfos.COUNTY_ROAD_INFO: County Road Access information: http://www.daggettcounty.org/index.aspx?nid=17 and http://www.utahcommuterlink.com/
huntBoundaryInfos.ATV_VEH_ACCESS:
Most roads and ATV trails on this unit are managed by the US Forest Service or BLM and are covered on their Travel Management Plans. Please direct all questions regarding which roads and trails ATVs can be operated on to the US Forest Service. There is no vehicle access allowed on Baretop.
Ashley National Forest: http://www.fs.usda.gov/detail/ashley/home/?cid=STELPRDB5432815
Uinta-Wasatch-Cache National Forest: http://www.fs.usda.gov
BLM: http://www.blm.gov/ut/st/en/fo/vernal.html
Most areas are closed to off road vehicle use except on designated routes.
huntBoundaryInfos.PRIV_TRIBE_LAND_ISSUES: The boundary of this hunt unit does not include Tribal Trust Lands and does not have much private land included.  Hunters should receive written permission from private landowners prior to the start of the hunts if they wish to hunt private property.
huntBoundaryInfos.BOUNDARY_DESCRIPTION: Daggett and Summit counties—Boundary begins at the Utah-Wyoming-Colorado state line (Three Corners); south on the Utah-Colorado state line to the Green River; west along the Green River to Flaming Gorge Reservoir; west along the south shoreline of Flaming Gorge Reservoir to Cart Creek; south along this creek to US-191; south on US-191 to the Uintah/Daggett county line (summit of the Uinta Mountains); west along this summit to the head of Burnt Fork drainage (Divide Pass/Island Lake); north along the Burnt Fork drainage bottom and Burnt Fork Creek to the Utah-Wyoming state line; east on this state line to the Utah-Wyoming-Colorado state line (Three Corners). USGS 1:100,000 Maps: Dutch John, Kings Peak.  Boundary questions?  Call the Vernal office, 435-781-9453.
